    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-Working-out-Rates-in-Real-Life-Situations">
        <title>Working out Rates in Real Life Situations</title>

        <activity>
            <p>
                <em><term>Work in Groups</term></em>
            </p>

            <p>
                Consider a phone has a data plan of <m>1</m> GB for Kshs <m>10</m> for an hour.
            </p>

            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Find the cost of surfing the internet for <m>30</m> minutes.
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Discusss and share with other groups.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </activity>

        <p>
            <md>
                <mrow> \amp {\color{blue} \text{Learning Point}} </mrow>
            </md>
        </p>

        <p>
            <me>
                \text{A rate is a ratio that compares two quantities measured in different units.}
            </me>
            
        </p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A car travels <m>100</m> miles in <m>2</m> hours. Find the rate of the car.
                </p>
            </statement>

            <solution>
                <p>
                    The rate of the car is <m>100</m> miles in <m>2</m> hours.
                </p>

                <p>
                    To calculate the rate, divide the distance by the time taken.
                </p>

                <p>
                    The rate of the car can be given by the formula:
                </p>

                <p>
                    <me>Rate = \frac{Distance}{Time}</me>
                </p>

                <p>
                    Substituting the values of distance and time, we get:
                </p>

                <p>
                    <me>Rate = \frac{100 \, miles}{2 \, hours}</me>
                </p>

                <p>
                    <me>Rate \, of \, speed = 50\, miles\, per\, hour </me> 
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A labourer digs <m>10</m> holes in <m>5</m> hours. Find the rate of digging holes.
                </p>
            </statement>

            <solution>
                <p>
                    The rate of digging holes is <m>10</m> holes in <m>5</m> hours.
                </p>

                <p>
                    To calculate the rate, divide the number of holes by the time taken.
                </p>

                <p>
                    The rate of digging holes can be given by the formula:
                </p>

                <p>
                    <me>Rate = \frac{Number\, of\, Holes}{Time}</me>
                </p>

                <p>
                    Substituting the values of number of holes and time, we get:
                </p>

                <p>
                    <me>Rate = \frac{10}{5}</me>
                </p>

                <p>
                    <me>Rate = 2 \, holes\, per\, hour</me> 
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A family of <m>4</m> consumes <m>20</m> litres of milk in <m>5</m> days. Find the rate of consumption of milk.
                </p>
            </statement>

            <solution>
                <p>
                    The rate of consumption of milk is <m>20</m> litres in <m>5</m> days.
                </p>

                <p>
                    To calculate the rate, divide the amount of milk by the time taken.
                </p>

                <p>
                    The rate of consumption of milk can be given by the formula:
                </p>

                <p>
                    <me>Rate = \frac{Amount\, of\, Milk}{Time}</me>
                </p>

                <p>
                    Substituting the values of amount of milk and time, we get:
                </p>

                <p>
                    <me>Rate = \frac{20}{5}</me>
                </p>

                <p>
                    <me>Rate = 4 \, litres\, per\, day</me>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        
    </subsubsection>
</subsection>